{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Adrian Beria Blog","author":"Adrian Beria"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"87609e98-734d-5452-ad69-7244bc4ef91b","excerpt":"Introduction Modals are one of my favorite UX assets to use as a user and developer, having all the information available in one place…","html":"<h2>Introduction</h2>\n<p>Modals are one of my favorite UX assets to use as a user and developer, having all the information available in one place presented in an elegant way makes it more pleasant for me. We’re going to check how to use modals using the library react-modal, which has more than one million weekly downloads and has a weight of 11.2kb, two aspects that are important when choosing a library.</p>\n<h2>When to use</h2>\n<p>The answer is whenever you need it, this is up to the designer in most cases, but I personally use it for forms and making UX more pleasant.</p>\n<h2>Installing dependencies</h2>\n<p>For an alredy created project:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"text\"><pre class=\"language-text\"><code class=\"language-text\">yarn add react-modal</code></pre></div>\n<h2>How to use</h2>\n<p>We will use the <a href=\"https://github.com/reactjs/react-modal\">doc example</a> and expand on it.</p>\n<p>In the component we <strong>import Modal from “react-modal”</strong>, which will act as a container for any children it has, making it versatile and reusable, lets see an example:</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/a4b29/react-modal-1.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 129.738933030647%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"code\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/fb8a0/react-modal-1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/1a291/react-modal-1.png 148w,\n/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/2bc4a/react-modal-1.png 295w,\n/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/fb8a0/react-modal-1.png 590w,\n/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/526de/react-modal-1.png 885w,\n/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/fa2eb/react-modal-1.png 1180w,\n/static/00ee38ab22fee6dd5dd8f6804e5f2d73/a4b29/react-modal-1.png 1762w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<p>The docs I linked earlier show what each props do.</p>\n<h2>Lets check how to use it in a component</h2>\n<p>We can start by doing:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"javascript\"><pre class=\"language-javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">[</span>modalIsOn<span class=\"token punctuation\">,</span> setModalIsOn<span class=\"token punctuation\">]</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token function\">useState</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token boolean\">false</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>We declare a state that controls wether the Modal should be activated or not. Then we create a function that will control the state.</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"javascript\"><pre class=\"language-javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token function-variable function\">showModal</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token function\">setModalIsOn</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span><span class=\"token operator\">!</span>value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span>\n<span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token function-variable function\">modalClosed</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> <span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token function\">setModalIsOn</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>value<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Now we can do:</p>\n<div class=\"gatsby-highlight\" data-language=\"javascript\"><pre class=\"language-javascript\"><code class=\"language-javascript\"><span class=\"token keyword\">const</span> <span class=\"token function-variable function\">onClick</span> <span class=\"token operator\">=</span> isModalOn <span class=\"token operator\">=></span> <span class=\"token function\">showModal</span><span class=\"token punctuation\">(</span>isModalOn<span class=\"token punctuation\">)</span></code></pre></div>\n<p>Add the onClick function to any component you want to make the modal show.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Import Router and Route inside App.js.</li>\n<li>Make Router your container and inside add all your routes, saying which path will be assigned to which component.</li>\n<li>Inside your Navbar, import Link and add it to your menus, so when they’re clicked they will take you to the component you want, the <strong>to</strong> prop needs to be the same as the Route.</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Conclusion</h2>\n<p>We check how to use React Router.</p>\n<p>See you on the next post.</p>\n<p>Sincerely,</p>\n<p><strong>Eng Adrian Beria.</strong></p>","frontmatter":{"title":"React Modal","date":"March 20, 2020"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/12-react-modal/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/10-redux-toolkit/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Redux Toolkit"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/11-react-router/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"React Router"}}}}